Senegals music best known abroad due the popularity mbalax development Serer sabar drumming popularized Youssou NDour During the colonial ages Senegal was colonized France and many though not all Senegalese identified French instead any African ethnicity Postindependence the philosophy negritude arose which espoused the idea that the griot traditions Senegal were valid classical and meaningful French classical music The first President Senegal Lopold Sdar Senghor also poet was one the primary exponents this The national anthem Senegal Pincez tous vos koras frappez les balafons Pluck all your koras strike the balafons was adopted 1960 Its lyrics president Senghor refer the Malian music tradition while its music was composed Herbert Pepper Ethnically the population Senegal 433 Wolof 238 Fula 147 Serer 147 Jola Mandinka and Soninka with European and Lebanese and classed other Senegalese music has been influenced that the Malian Empire though tends fast and lively whereas the sounds Malian griots are sedate classical Mbalax meaning rhythm Wolofderives its from accompanying rhythms used sabar music the Serer people the Kingdom Sine and spread the Kingdom Saloum whence Wolof migrants brought the Wolof kingdoms The Nder lead drum Sabar rhythm drum and Tama talking drum percussion section traces some its technique the ritual music Njuup The Serer people infuse their everyday language with complex overlapping cadences and their ritual with intense collaborative layerings voice and rhythm The Njuup was also the progenitor Tassu used when chanting ancient religious verses The griots Senegambia still use marriages naming ceremonies when singing the praises patrons Most Senegalese and Gambian artists use their songs Each motif has purpose and used for different occasions Individual motifs may represent the history and genealogy particular family and are used during weddings naming ceremonies funerals etc Senegalese popular music can traced back the 1960s when nightclubs hosted dance bands orchestres that played Western music Ibra Kasses Star Band was the most famous orchestre After beginning playing American Cuban and French songs Star Band gradually added more indigenous elements including the talking tama drum and Wolof Mandinkalanguage lyrics Star Band disintegrated into numerous groups with Pape Secks Number One Senegal being the best known the next wave bands followed Orchestra Baobab The south Senegal called Casamance has strong Mandinka minority and began producing masters the kora the late 1950s The band Tour Kunda was the most popular group arise from this scene and they soon began playing large concerts across the world 1977 the entire rhythm section and many other performers the Star Band left form toile Dakar who quickly eclipsed their compatriots and launched the careers Hadji Faye and Youssou NDour Faye and NDour were Senegals first pop stars but the stress fame soon drove the band apart Faye and guitarist Badou Ndiaye formed toile 2000 releasing hit with Boubou NGary but soon disappearing from the pop scene NDour however went form Super toile Dakar and his career continued was soon far the most popular performer the country and perhaps all West Africa introduced more traditional elements his Senegalized Cuban music including traditional rapping tassou njuup bakou music kind trilling that accompanies Serer wrestling and instruments like the sabar While NDour Africanized Cuban music another influential band Xalam was doing the same with American funk and jazz They formed 1970 led then drummer Prosper Niang but their controversial lyrics and unfamiliar jazz sound led lack popularity and the group moved Paris 1973 There they added JeanPhilippe Rykiel keyboards Xalam toured with groups such Rolling Stones and Crosby Stills Nash Young finally achieving success Senegal with 1988s Xarit the latter part the 1970s the band Super Diamono formed fusing mbalax rhythms and militant populism with jazz and reggae influences Their 1982 Jigenu Ndakaru was especially popular the middle the 1980s Super Diamono was one the top bands Senegal close and fierce competition with Super toile Dakar The bands popularity declined however slowed somewhat Omar Penes reformation 1991 This mix example mostly Senegalese music from the 1970s and 1980s but some other African countries are represented well httpssoundcloudcomtrushmixtrushmix85kokknroll Into the 1990s Thione Seck griot descended from those Lat Dior the king Kayor arose solo stardome from Orchestra Baobab eventually forming his own band called Raam Daan crawl slowly towards your goal used electric instruments many popular releases especially Diongoma and Demb The same period saw the rise Ismael member Super Diamono who had major hits including Attaya Ceddo and Jele Baaba Maal another popular Senegalese singer from Podor and won scholarship study music Paris After returning studied traditional music with his blind guitarist and family griot Mansour Seck and began performing with the band Daande Lenol His Djam Leelii recorded 1984 became critical sensation the United Kingdom after was released there 1989 Maals fusions continued into the next decade with his Firin Fouta 1994 album which used ragga salsa and Breton harp music create popular sound that launched the careers Positive Black Soul group rappers and also led the formation the AfroCelt Sound System His fusion tendencies continued 1998s Nomad Soul which featured Brian Eno one seven producers Though female performers were achieving popular breakthroughs elsewhere West Africa especially Mali Senegalese women had few opportunities before the 1990s The first international release woman was Cheikh Anta Mbacke 1989 Kin Lam The songs success led string female performers including Fatou Guewel Madiodio Gning Daro Mbaye and Khar Mbaye Madiaga Lam however remained perhaps the most influential female musician the 1990s creating modernized version sabar xalam ensembles adding bass guitar and synthesizer with 1993s Su